I have some opinions on this but will refrain atm.. instead i give to you the rush-wing side of things and would like to know your thoughts....other then &quot;rush is a moron!&quot; heheh Zort.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;The GOP needs to unleash attacks on the Democrats like Kent Conrad - who's out there saying $500 billion will be &quot;raided&quot; from this imaginary Social Security trust fund the liberals like Conrad and Tom Daschle are so obsessed with. Daschle said on CNN's Inside Politics Tuesday night, &quot;The real concern I have is what's going to happen to education, what's going to happen to the Medicare program, what's going to happen to defense and to all the other high priorities the government has had.&quot; <br>
   <br>
   <br>
   <br>
  What about the &quot;high priorities&quot; America's families can't fund because they have to pay your confiscatory taxes or get thrown in jail? Folks, these Democrats are trying to rip Bush a new one on this non-existent Social Security trust fund, as if the government isn't fully funded to the tune of $2,000,000,000,000. These attacks must not be of the kinds that whine about the unfairness of the Democrats' statements and ads. Instead, they must explain how the Democrats raised taxes on Social Security recipients back in the early 90s and how the Democrats refused to fix Medicare, thereby cutting such benefits as cancer treatments in doctors' offices. This is not hard. I've been doing it here for years! <br>
<br>
I don't know why we are beginning to respond to these people by using their terminology and accepting their premises in our arguments. There is no trust fund to protect. All the money you pay in Social Security taxes ends up in the general fund. We have to point this out. Bush and his people need to say, &quot;Look, we haven't done one thing but shore up Social Security. We have plans designed to make it viable long-term. We want people to benefit from Social Security even more than they always have,&quot; and then explain the privatization plan that you've got. <br>
 <br>
   <br>
   <br>
   <br>
   <br>
<br>
Bush needs to use the bully pulpit on this one. He can't tell the Democrats we're going to work with them on not taking unnecessary funds from this trust fund when no such trust fund exists. The Republicans and the administration must explain that the Democrats are always spending. They want to spend more money than ever before - and all sources of revenue, whether from FICA or the Medicare tax or individual income taxes, corporate taxes, estate tax, airline tax, electricity tax, telephone tax, whatever, must be used to pay for their spending spree. <br>
<br>
Back to my old question: How is it that only tax cuts dip into some so-called surplus when spending doesn't? The fact is, there's far more spending going on here than there are tax cuts, and this tax cut is so back loaded, it's not nearly large enough to be causing any of these problems. The economy has slowed down, such that there is less income coming into the government because of lower tax receipts. That's the main reason, coupled with spending, for the shrinking surplus - which ought to shrink anyway entirely because it represents over-taxation. <br>
<br>
Remember, there was no talk of raiding the Social Security trust fund during the early years of the Clinton administration when the budget was still in deficit. There was no talk of raiding the Social Security trust fund when Tom Daschle voted for the Reagan tax cut of '81. There was no talk of raiding the Social Security tax fund to pay for six, seven, or eight percent increase in the budget demanded by today's Democrats. <br>
<br>
What's needed here is a little straightforward explaining, and a new political strategy by the Republicans, one that does not accept the lies and distortions of the Democrats. The Democrats harmed Social Security recipients and Medicare recipients. Bush hasn't done anything to harm anybody. The only thing Bush has attempted to do is make the programs stronger. Why they don't just come out and say so is beyond me. &quot;<br>
